{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17501373","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17501373"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:28:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:28:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1754"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1754"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.63,0.06,0.05,0.16,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82670"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1754"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67816"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"912"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2658"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2728"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28277"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82670","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82670"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 55-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with three days of worsening breathlessness, bifrontal headache, and light-headedness. He has a medical history of atrial fibrillation and hypertension. His medications include apixaban and perindopril. He has a 40 pack-year smoking history and works as a builder.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears distressed. His pulse rate is 115/min, blood pressure 155/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 26/min, SpO2 96% on oxygen 4 L/min, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There is marked facial and neck swelling with prominent neck vein distension. His chest examination reveals no added sounds.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["CT chest with contrast","Ventilation-perfusion scan","MRI brain","Transthoracic echocardiogram","CT pulmonary angiogram"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of superior vena cava (SVC) syndrome, characterised by facial and neck swelling, dyspnoea, and headache. These symptoms result from obstruction of venous return through the SVC, most commonly caused by malignancy in the thorax.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT chest with contrast\u003C/strong\u003E is the investigation of choice as it can identify the cause and extent of SVC obstruction, typically showing the mass and its relationship to surrounding structures. It can also guide biopsy planning if needed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentilation-perfusion scan\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if pulmonary embolism was suspected, but would not show SVC obstruction. While patients with malignancy are at increased risk of venous thromboembolism, the facial and neck swelling point more strongly toward SVC syndrome.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMRI brain\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if there was concern about central nervous system pathology, but would not explain the constellation of symptoms including facial and neck swelling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransthoracic echocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E might show indirect signs of SVC obstruction but would not clearly demonstrate the cause or extent of obstruction. It would be more appropriate if heart failure was suspected.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECT pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is specifically designed to look for pulmonary embolism. While it might incidentally show an obstructing mass, a CT chest with contrast is better optimised to show the SVC and surrounding structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven this patient\u0027s significant smoking history, lung cancer would be the most likely underlying cause. After confirming SVC syndrome on imaging, tissue diagnosis and staging would guide definitive management, which may include chemotherapy, radiotherapy, or stenting of the SVC.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Superior vena cava syndrome commonly presents with facial and neck swelling, dyspnoea, and headache.","Lung cancer is the most common cause of superior vena cava syndrome.","CT chest with contrast is the diagnostic investigation of choice for superior vena cava syndrome."],"references":["Drews RE, Rabkin DJ. Malignancy-related superior vena cava syndrome. In: Bruera E, Eidt JE, Mills JL, Mullner NL editors.;\u200bUpToDate. [Internet]. Waltham (MA): UpToDate Inc; 2021. [updated 2021 Feb 11; cited 2021 May 10]. Available from:  https://www.uptodate.com/contents/malignancy-related-superior-vena-cava-syndrome"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67816"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1754"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67816","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67816"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T19:30:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T19:31:49+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1754"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82670"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"rel